SIMPLE: inspire
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inspire
<hw>In*spire"</hw> <pr>(⟦icr⟧n*sp⟦imac⟧r")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<ety>[OE. <ets>enspiren</ets>, OF. <ets>enspirer</ets>,
<ets>inspirer</ets>, F. <ets>inspirer</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>inspirare</ets>; pref. <ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>spirare</ets> to
breathe. See <er>Spirit</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To breathe into; to fill with the breath; to
animate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When Zephirus eek, with his sweete breath,⟦br⟧
<qex>Inspir⟦egrave⟧d</qex> hath in every holt and heath⟦br⟧
The tender crops.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Descend, ye Nine, descend and sing,⟦br⟧
The breathing instruments <qex>inspire</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To infuse by breathing, or as if by
breathing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He knew not his Maker, and him that <qex>inspired</qex> into him
an active soul.</q> <rj><qau>Wisdom xv. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To draw in by the operation of breathing; to inhale;
-- opposed to <ant>expire</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Forced to <qex>inspire</qex> and expire the air with
difficulty.</q> <rj><qau>Harvey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 771 --></p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To infuse into the mind; to communicate to the
spirit; to convey, as by a divine or supernatural influence; to disclose
preternaturally; to produce in, as by inspiration.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And generous stout courage did <qex>inspire</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>But dawning day new comfort hath <qex>inspired</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To infuse into; to affect, as with a superior or
supernatural influence; to fill with what animates, enlivens, or exalts;
to communicate inspiration to; <as>as, to <ex>inspire</ex> a child with
sentiments of virtue; to <ex>inspire</ex> a person to do extraordinary
feats</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>Erato, thy poet's mind <qex>inspire</qex>,⟦br⟧
And fill his soul with thy celestial fire.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inspire</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Inspire
<hw>In*spire"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Inspired</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Inspiring</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To draw in breath; to inhale air into the lungs; --
opposed to <ant>expire</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To breathe; to blow gently.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And when the wind amongst them did <qex>inspire</qex>,⟦br⟧
They wav⟦egrave⟧d like a penon wide dispread.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inspired</ent>⟦br⟧
